d judge famous for his prodigious strength. He was betrayed by his mistress, Delilah, and enslaved and blinded by the Philistines; nevertheless, he was able to bring the pillars of the temple of the Philistines crashing down in a final suicidal act of strength (Judges 13–16). This famous story provided the theme for  Milton's  poetic drama Samson Agonistes (  1671 ), which is modelled on ancient Greek tragedy. In the Middle Ages the popularity of the given name was increased in Celtic areas by the fame of a 6th-century Celtic saint who bore it, probably as a classicized form of some ancient Celtic name. He was a Welsh monk who did missionary work in Cornwall and afterwards established a monastery at Dol in Brittany."],"variants":[{"name":"Sampson","meanings":["The Greek form of the Scripture name, which Simonis translates, 'sol eximius,' i.e. illustrious sun; the Rev. A. Jones 'splendid sun,' i.e. great joy and felicity; Tregelles, ' solar, like the sun; ' and Fuerstius, ' sonnenahnlicher ' that is, one who resembles the sun (from shemesh, the sun)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Samson de Wasseborne was born in 1116, in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Samson FitzGodard de Wasseborne I. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1116–":"1116–Surnud","1115–Male":"1115–Surnud","1141–Male":"1141–Surnud","1116–Female":"1116–Surnud","1116":"1116","1115":"1115","1141":"1141","Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1116–":"1116–Kuollut","1115–Male":"1115–Kuollut","1141–Male":"1141–Kuollut","1116–Female":"1116–Kuollut","1116":"1116","1115":"1115","1141":"1141","Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1116–":"1116–Décédée","1115–Male":"1115–Décédé","1141–Male":"1141–Décédé","1116–Female":"1116–Décédée","1116":"1116","1115":"1115","1141":"1141","Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummar